1. THE NEURO-MECHANISTIC IMPERATIVE: BEYOND WRITTEN DELIBERATION
-----------------------------------------------------------------

In the deployment of autonomous language agents, ensuring safety and logical consistency is typically treated as a linguistic compliance task. Developers write system prompts containing lists of rules, examples, or negative commands (e.g., "Never execute raw shell commands," "Do not expose sensitive directory variables"). 

When agents are tasked with complex, long-horizon operations, developers often rely on Chain-of-Thought (CoT) prompting, requiring the model to verbalize its reasoning step-by-step on the page before proposing an action.

While conversational prompting and CoT are standard, they suffer from three fundamental systems-level limitations:

### 1.1 Softmax Attention Dilution
Self-attention weights are calculated as a normalized exponential (softmax) over all preceding tokens in the sequence. As the sequence length N scales to tens of thousands of tokens, the mathematical weight allocated to early system instructions decays toward zero. The model loses its "latent grip" on the rules, allowing intermediate task details and conversational noise to dominate its attention.

### 1.2 The "White Bear" Priming Effect
Standard negative instructions (such as "Do not use evaluate") are highly fragile in unstructured formats. Because the negative command is written as flat text, it serves as a semantic prime, loading the forbidden concept into the model's active workspace and paradoxically increasing the probability of generating the unsafe token.

### 1.3 The Agreeability Trap
Language models are trained to optimize for conversational plausibility. If a user submits a manipulative prompt designed to bypass safety boundaries, an unconstrained model will experience representation drift. It will construct a highly compliant-sounding reasoning trace that completely masks the generation of an unsafe or operationally broken command, prioritizing looking helpful over maintaining underlying systems invariants.

