3. THE XML SCHEMA: A FIRST-PRINCIPLES WORKSPACE INTERFACE
---------------------------------------------------------

To program the model's J-space directly, we introduce a structured, multi-axis XML schema that acts as an active attention-pruning interface in the prompt prefix. Instead of writing system instructions as flat paragraphs, we divide constraints into explicit constructive and restrictive axes under a semantic justification:

```
                  STRUCTURED XML PATTERN ANATOMY
+------------------------------------------------------------------+
| <pattern domain="[domain]" name="[pattern name]">               |
|                                                                  |
|   <why>                                                          |
|     [Semantic justification: aligns vector coordinates]          |
|   </why>                                                         |
|                                                                  |
|   <how>                                                          |
|     [Constructive blueprint: sets target attractor manifold]     |
|   </how>                                                         |
|                                                                  |
|   <pitfall>                                                      |
|     [Restrictive boundary: acts as active attention pruner]      |
|   </pitfall>                                                     |
|                                                                  |
| </pattern>                                                       |
+------------------------------------------------------------------+
```

### 3.1 The Justification Axis (`<why>`)
This block outlines the underlying physical, logical, or mathematical rationale for the constraint. It provides the high-level semantic context, ensuring the pattern's embedding aligns with the conceptual intent of the task during vector retrieval.

### 3.2 The Constructive Axis (`<how>`)
The `<how>` tag provides the direct, positive-space blueprints and specific systems-hardened code patterns. This functions as a constructive attractor, pulling the model's intermediate hidden states toward safe, structurally sound execution patterns.

### 3.3 The Restrictive Axis (`<pitfall>`)
The `<pitfall>` tag defines the explicit, negative-space boundaries. It lists the precise, concrete tokens representing the target vulnerabilities (such as `+ ".tmp"`, `open(path, "w")`, or `os.path.exists`). By isolating the prohibited path, this tag provides a high-contrast target for the model's attention heads, acting as an active attention-pruning operator.

