7. IMPLEMENTATION GUIDELINES AND SYSTEM BOUNDARIES
-------------------------------------------------

While engineering the J-space via the XML schema provides a robust alternative to verbose Chain-of-Thought, developers must account for specific technical boundaries:

### 7.1 Limit Active Patterns to 3 to 10 Cards
Because the active global workspace of a transformer is limited to approximately $K \approx 25$ concurrent vectors, loading too many patterns into a single prompt will trigger **Workspace Displacement**. Earlier patterns will be systematically evicted from the active attention matrix to make room for incoming sequence tokens. Keep the system prompt lean, using between **5 and 8 active pattern cards** tailored specifically to the immediate task domain.

### 7.2 Maximize Contrast inside the `<pitfall>` Tag
Avoid generic, high-entropy phrasing (e.g., *"Do not write buggy code"*). Populate your `<pitfall>` tags with the highly specific, concrete tokens representing the target anti-pattern. This ensures that any activation state drifting toward those specific keywords triggers an immediate Query-Key alignment spike, activating safety-aligned attention pathways to prune the unsafe transition.

